{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d011895a-bd2e-4904-9937-af6dfd37947d","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` only tells the page not to pad for system UI overlaps. You likely still have **app-level chrome** (Shell navbar, NavigationPage bar) eating space, and on Android you may need transparent system bars. Here's the full recipe:\n\n### XAML — PhotoViewerPage.xaml\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             x:Class=\"YourApp.PhotoViewerPage\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\">\n\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n### Key things you're likely missing:\n\n1. **Hide app navigation chrome** — `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` (if using Shell) or `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"` (if using NavigationPage). These add their own bars with padding.\n\n2. **Android transparent system bars** — In .NET 10, Android 15+ enforces edge-to-edge, but the system bar backgrounds may still be opaque. Make them transparent in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnCreate((activity, _) =>\n    {\n        activity.Window!.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        activity.Window!.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n3. **`Aspect=\"AspectFill\"`** — Without this, the image preserves its aspect ratio and won't fill all available space.\n\n### Checklist\n| Issue | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| Shell navbar visible | `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` |\n| Shell tab bar visible | `Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"` |\n| NavigationPage bar | `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"` |\n| iOS safe area insets | `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` ✅ (you have this) |\n| Android opaque system bars | Set transparent via `Window` APIs |\n| Image doesn't fill | `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"96d4a5de-6393-4b8b-890f-437f3fc994eb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working on a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but it's not working.\n\nLet me think about what's needed for edge-to-edge display in .NET MAUI on .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET 10, MAUI introduced edge-to-edge display support, particularly on Android. The key things to know:\n\n1. **Android edge-to-edge**: Starting with .NET 10 / Android 15+, apps run edge-to-edge by default. But you need to handle it properly.\n\n\n2. **`SafeAreaEdges`** is primarily an iOS feature that prevents content from being inset for the safe area. On iOS, setting it to `None` should allow content to extend behind the status bar and home indicator.\n3. On **Android** with .NET 10, edge-to-edge is the default behavior, so the approach differs from iOS.\n\nFor Android specifically, I need to consider how window insets are handled by default and whether there's a way to opt out of the automatic inset behavior that keeps content away from system bars. The `NavigationBar` and `StatusBar` transparency settings likely play a role in achieving true edge-to-edge rendering on Android. On Android specifically, I need to make the system bars transparent so content can extend behind them, which in .NET 10 involves configuring the window styles or using platform-specific code to enable edge-to-edge rendering and prevent the system from applying window insets automatically. The most common culprit is usually Shell or NavigationPage adding their own padding, but I should also check whether the Android system window insets are still being applied despite the transparent bars, and make sure the Image's Aspect is set to AspectFill so it actually fills the space.","outputTokens":1849,"requestId":"B809:2CC3E:17B945:1F2832:69FFDA8F"},"id":"1bf6d7e6-e0a7-469a-8da8-c25140cc3d0e","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:09:10.394Z","parentId":"5332b841-4628-47d4-bc7b-d6ebfb6de3d2"}
